observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the following:

MA together with the PESO Manager to: 

submit the lacking documents to the AT for further evaluation of the transaction; 


ensure that all pertinent documents, as discussed above, are attached to the disbursement vouchers and liquidation reports in adherence to Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 to substantiate the legality, validity, and propriety of the said transactions;
 
submit justification on the compliance of the LGU with the 20 percent equity or counterpart as stipulated in the MOA and accordance with the DO; 
 
PESO Manager to exercise diligence and prudence in the identification and selection of beneficiaries to ensure that only qualified and eligible individuals received the financial assistance; and
 
MA to grant only cash advances within the maximum cash accountability covered by the accountable officer’s fidelity bond.



We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor include the concerned department heads in the meetings of special projects to inform and engage them in the implementation thereof.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the following:

Officer-in-Charge of Balay Silangan to:

prepare and submit a monthly summary list of enrollees to the Treasurer's Office;


send demand letters, monitor the number of demand letters already sent, and evaluate if another course of action is needed;
 
analyze why most of the clients could not pay their obligations and, based on that analysis, develop a scheme on how to address the said problem within the agency level, especially in the manner of collection; 

Closely monitor the operations of Balay Silangan to avoid overdrafts in the disbursement of funds.



MT to prepare and submit the Monthly Summary List of Statement of Accounts to the Accounting Office; and


MA to:

1. Effect the following journal entries to record the accrual of revenue for CY 2021 and CY 2022 as follows:


Adopt the accrual basis of accounting in recording revenues for Balay Silangan and maintain schedules and subsidiary ledgers.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare and maintain RAO for all budgetary items that would facilitate in the proper preparation of SCBAA;
Stop relying on the records maintained by Municipal Budget Officer, instead reconcile RAOs regularly with budget records to ensure accuracy of amounts recorded;
Prepare the reconciliation of SCBAA with other financial statements properly with reconciling items traceable in available accounting information; and
Trace irregular reconciling items namely, “Others” amounting ₱6,703,317.70 in working schedules, accounting records, and registries to ensure the accuracy of savings to be declared from CY 2023.

We recommended that Management direct the:

MT to:

strictly implement the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code in order to correct the assessment and collection of business taxes that will accrue to the municipality;

conduct verification on transactions recorded by the municipality and compare it to the amount of sales declared on renewal of business permits; 

conduct regular inspection and verification of financial records of the business establishments to ensure that the correct gross receipts will be declared by the taxpayer;

maintain periodic reviews together with concerned officials to ascertain whether collection targets are attained. Those reasons for the shortfall in collections should be analyzed and alternative methods or procedures be undertaken to avoid the incurrence of shortfall in the future; 

Business and Permits Licensing Officer (MBPLO) to:

refrain from accepting application for the renewal of business permits that are not based on the documentary requirements like the audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration particularly when the taxpayer submit the prior year’s gross receipts in rounded figures;

require submission of complete documentation of the financial records from taxpayers for the correct assessment of taxes; and

maintain and use an individual ledger or index card for each business establishment in recording their tax payment.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

direct the Processing Center Manager to fast track the preparation of the Accomplishment Reports, and submit the same to oversight bodies such as the DOST, the Audit Team, and the Management;

properly account the receipts and expenditures of the Food Processing Center by seeking the assistance of the Municipal Accountant, in order to provide a better insight on the financial position and performance of the project;

ensure that all collections received by the Food Processing Center are remitted to the Local Treasurer daily and intact; and

prepare regular payrolls for the payment of wages for the laborers instead of directly deducting them from collections.

the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer to conduct monthly reconciliation of budget and actual amounts. Also, trace the unreconciled balance amounting to P3,148,354.37 to fairly present the SCBAA;
the Municipal Accountant  and the Municipal Budget Officer to take mindful considerations in interpreting the pertinent provisions of IPSAS 24 on how the SCBAA, including its reconciliation statement with the other financial statements, is being prepared; and
the Municipal Accountant to present the expenses totaling P602,632.50 as valid reconciling items in the SCBAA.

Municipal Treasurer to:
Strictly implement the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code in order to correct the assessment and collection of business taxes that will accrue to the Municipality;
Conduct verification on transactions recorded by the Municipality and compare it to the amount of sales declared on renewal of business permits;
Conduct regular inspection and verification of financial records of the business establishments to ensure that the correct gross receipts will be declared by the taxpayer;
Set up or institutionalize a standard computation that could arrive in a more realistic basis of business taxes in the absence of the required audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration of the gross receipts;
Maintain periodic reviews together with concerned officials to ascertain whether collection targets are attained. Those reasons for the shortfall in collections should be analyzed and alternative methods or procedures be undertaken to avoid the incurrence of shortfall in the future;
Business and Permits Licensing Officer (MBPLO) to:
Refrain from accepting application for the renewal of business permits that are not based on the documentary requirements like the audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration particularly when the taxpayer submit the prior year’s gross receipts in rounded figures;
Require submission of complete documentation of the financial records from taxpayers for the correct assessment of taxes; and
Maintain and use an individual ledger or index card for each business establishment in recording their tax payment.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive  (LCE):

direct the Building Official to:  a) provide status on those issued building permits without occupancy permits and impose necessary fees for completed projects, and thereafter, monitor those issued with building permits to secure occupancy permits first before actually occupying the structures constructed; b) submit the building permits and occupancy permits issued per month to the Municipal Assessor in order to update the Tax Assessment Roll;


continuously tap the Barangay Officials to report to Building Official monthly/quarterly the on-going construction and completed structures in their barangays in order to facilitate the Building Official in monitoring compliance of the structures with the National Building Code of the Philippines and maximize income generated therewith;

enjoin the Task Force BZETA to religiously monitor newly constructed buildings, whether commercial or residential; and

direct the Municipal Assessor to verify whether real properties within the Municipality are properly listed in the assessment rolls specifically those newly constructed or renovated.

We have recommended that:

the BAC and the TWG conduct post qualification by verifying, validating, and ascertaining all statements made and documents submitted by the bidder with the Lowest Calculated Bid and ensure that the Post-Qualification Report contains in-depth results on the verification of technical requirements; 

the BAC and the TWG, before recommending award of contracts with simultaneous or overlapping periods of implementation to the same contractor, ensure that the contractor has sufficient personnel and equipment to undertake the projects.  Otherwise, disqualify future bids whose key personnel and equipment are already pledged /used in other on-going projects;

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct:

the various Heads of Office or Department to keep record of all items of PPE under his charge, and render his accounts therefore semi-annually to the Municipal Mayor;




the General Services Officer to conduct a more complete inventory of the items of PPE, and rely on multiple records to ascertain the completeness of information, to which existence may be compared;






the General Services Officer to update her records, especially on accountability over items of PPE, to determine responsibility and facilitate proper turnover of accountability; and





the Recordkeeper of documents pertaining to Land to register for titles to protect the interest of the Municipality over the said properties.

With the foregoing, we have recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

direct the Processing Center Manager to fast track the preparation of the Accomplishment Reports, and submit the same to oversight bodies such as the DOST, the audit team, and Management;
properly account the receipts and expenditures of the Food Processing Center by seeking the assistance of the Municipal Accountant, in order to provide a better insight on the financial position and performance of the project;
ensure that all collections received by the Food Processing Center are remitted to the Local Treasurer, daily and intact; and
prepare regular payrolls for the payment of wages for the laborers instead of directly deducting them from collections.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

direct the Building to Official to a) provide status on those issued building permits without occupancy permits and impose necessary fees for completed projects, and thereafter, monitor those issued with building permits to secure occupancy permits first before actually occupying the structures constructed; b) submit the building permits and occupancy permits issued per month to the Municipal Assessor in order to update the Tax Assessment Roll;
continuously tap the Barangay Officials to report to Building Official monthly/quarterly the on-going construction and completed structures in their barangays in order to facilitate the Building Official in monitoring compliance of the structures with the National Building Code of the Philippines and maximize income generated therewith;
enjoin the Task Force BZETA to religiously monitor newly constructed buildings, whether commercial or residential; and
direct the Municipal Assessor to verify whether real properties within the municipality are properly listed in the assessment rolls specifically those newly constructed or renovated.

Based on the foregoing observations we have, therefore, recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct:
The various Heads of Office or Department to keep record of all items of PPE under his charge, and render his accounts therefor semi-annually to the Municipal Mayor;
The General Services Officer to conduct a more complete inventory of the items of PPE, and rely on multiple records to ascertain the completeness of information, to which existence may be compared;
The General Services Officer to update her records, especially on accountability over items of PPE, to determine responsibility and facilitate proper turnover of accountability; and
The Recordkeeper of documents pertaining to Land to register for titles to protect the interest of the Municipality over the said properties.

Strictly enforce waste segregation at source in order to achieve the primary objective to protect the environment and public health from substantial, present, and potential hazard of solid wastes;
Strictly monitor the implementation of Ordinance No. 20-2011 in order to reduce plastic wastes; and
Promote Solid Waste Management Awareness through, proactive Information and Education Campaigns (IEC) in coordination with the Barangay Solid Waste Management Committees and academic institutions i.e. seminars/trainings/forums, informative and visually striking related signages posted in conspicuous areas, use of social media in information dissemination, etc.
